"{\n  \"text\": \"Hey everybody, this is my chicken tractor. I learned this from Joel Salicton in the book You Can't Farm. That's a great book. Got me into the whole venture of uh gardening and stuff. And uh this thing is like 17 generations. Every time it uh breaks, I just kind of build around every time it rots, I build around that, and like I I just don't even stop until like one day it's gonna completely collapse. But until that day I just keep building it, it's a little bit heavy now. Uh the wheels are good though. Uh everything on it's been scavenged from something else. There's nothing that I purchased except for the roof, and that was six years ago. So uh it's done pretty well. I've had to reinforce it because uh a couple times, well once, predators got through an inn. It was a cat, and they're so sneaky and good at it. Uh I caught it. Uh but it killed a couple more chickens, and um when I say I caught it, I didn't catch it. I saw it in my backyard. Uh but I've had to uh cat proof everything, and so all that happens. But the main deal with this uh uh chicken tractor is that it moves so you don't have to, and there's the inside. Chickens like perches more than flat things, I find out. So like if you give them the option, especially from early on, they generally will perch. And so when they perch, they'll be right over open ground. You move the tractor, most of the poo from the night goes on the ground, and that's great. I just moved this recently, but there's a bunch of poo on the ground. So it distributes it, distributes it, and you never have to move it around. Of course, the back end opens up to the nester, and I have three eggs. I'm gonna set these down for a second. Close that up. Anyway, uh I just want to talk to you about my chicken tractor. Uh it's one of the most important things about owning a uh chickens. Don't make a coop. Put it on wheels, have it so it can move around. It's a really it's a great time saver. Thanks, Joel Salatin. Appreciate that 